House Prices - Advanced Regression Techniques

Problem Statement¶

Ask a home buyer to describe their dream house, and they probably won't begin with the height of the basement ceiling or the proximity to an east-west railroad. But this playground competition's dataset proves that much more influences price negotiations than the number of bedrooms or a white-picket fence.

With 79 explanatory variables describing (almost) every aspect of residential homes in Ames, Iowa, this competition challenges you to predict the final price of each home.

# Function to convert datatype to category
def convert_type(data, features):
    for feature in features:
        data[feature] = data[feature].astype('category')
        
    return data

Correlation¶

We will use spearman correlation to identify relationship between numeric features and dependent variable

In [59]:
# Function to return spearman coeffient for numerical features
def correlation_spearman(data, features, saleprice):
    correlations = pd.DataFrame()
    correlations["features"] = features
    
    # Calculating spearman correlation
    correlations["Correlation"] = [data[i].corr(saleprice, 'spearman') for i in features]
    
    # Sort with respective to correlation
    correlations.sort_values('Correlation', inplace = True)
    correlations.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)
    
    return correlations

ANOVA test¶

We will perform one way anova to identify categorical features having higher impact on SalePrice

In [68]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway
def anova_test(data, categorical_features, y):
    data = pd.concat([data, y], axis = 1)
    anova = pd.DataFrame()
    anova['features']  = categorical_features
    pvalues = list()
    for category in categorical_features:
        samples = []
        for cls in data[category].unique():
            s = data[data[category] == cls]['SalePrice'].values
            samples.append(s)
        pvalue = f_oneway(*samples)[1]
        pvalues.append(pvalue)
    
    anova['pvalues'] = pvalues
    anova.sort_values('pvalues', inplace = True)
    anova.reset_index(drop  = True, inplace = True)
    return anova

import xgboost as xgb
from xgboost.sklearn import XGBRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

1. Hyperparameter Tuning

GridSearchCV params:

  • estimator: estimator object
  • param_grid : dict or list of dictionaries
  • scoring: A single string or a callable to evaluate the predictions on the test set. If None, the estimators score method is used.
  • n_jobs: Number of jobs to run in parallel. None means. -1 means using all processors.
  • cv: cross-validation, None, to use the default 3-fold cross validation. Integer, to specify the number of folds in a (Stratified)KFold.

Hyper Parameters :

  • learning rate - Learning rate for training model
  • early_stopping_rounds - The number of rounds without improvements after which we should stop
  • max_depth - It is the maximum number of nodes allowed from the root to the farthest leaf of a tree
  • min_child_weight - It is the minimum weight required in order to create a new node in the tree.
  • subsample - Subsample ratio of the training instances. Setting it to 0.5 means that XGBoost would randomly sample half of the training data prior to growing trees. and this will prevent overfitting.
  • colsample_bytree - specify the fraction of columns to be subsampled.
In [116]:
def hyperParameterTuning(X_train, y_train):
    param_tuning = {
        'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1],
        'max_depth': [3, 5, 7, 10],
        'min_child_weight': [1, 3, 5],
        'subsample': [0.5, 0.7],
        'colsample_bytree': [0.5, 0.7],
        'n_estimators' : [100, 200, 500],
        'objective': ['reg:squarederror']
    }

    xgb_model = XGBRegressor()

    gsearch = GridSearchCV(estimator = xgb_model,
                           param_grid = param_tuning,                        
                           cv = 3,
                           n_jobs = -1,
                           verbose = 1)

    gsearch.fit(X_train,y_train)

    return gsearch.best_params_

def include_train_dummies(train, test):
    a = list(train.columns.values)
    b = list(test.columns.values)
    c = [i for i in a if i not in b]
    k = [0 for j in range(1459)]
    indexs = []
    for i in c:
        indexs.append(a.index(i))
    
    for i in range(len(c)):
        test.insert(indexs[i], c[i], k)
        
    return test
